eligible_collateral.notes: Successfully processed CASH_USD collateral type with high confidence. The collateral represents US Dollar cash, which is the most straightforward asset class requiring no maturity bucketing. Initial parse was clean with standard 100% valuation and 0% haircut, consistent with cash being the highest quality collateral. Ambiguity detection phase found no issues across 6 validation passes. Resolution step achieved 0.885 confidence, indicating strong agreement on the straightforward nature of cash collateral. Both taxonomy and logic validation passed without corrections. The processing pipeline required no self-corrections, and the final output aligns with standard market practices for cash collateral treatment. Minor confidence reduction from perfect score (0.05) accounts for the inherent uncertainty in any automated parsing system, though this represents a best-case scenario with minimal complexity.

Successfully parsed US Treasury collateral with 0.5% haircut (99.5% valuation). Processing involved 6 initial parse attempts, 6 ambiguity detection passes, and 6 resolution cycles with confidence scores ranging from 0.786 to 0.936. No maturity bucket differentiation was specified, resulting in a single universal bucket. All taxonomy and logic validations passed. The moderate confidence reflects the multiple processing iterations required and variance in resolution confidence scores, though the final output structure is valid and consistent.

Successfully processed US Treasury collateral with uniform 2% haircut across all maturities. Initial parse completed by haiku model, followed by ambiguity detection across 6 iterations. Ambiguity resolution performed by sonnet model with 4 successful passes (confidence scores: 0.885, 0.936, 0.860, 0.920). All outputs passed taxonomy and logic validation. No maturity bucket differentiation detected, resulting in single bucket with null maturity bounds. High confidence due to: (1) consistent ambiguity resolution across multiple passes, (2) successful validation at each step, (3) clear collateral type identification, and (4) straightforward haircut structure. Minor confidence reduction due to lack of maturity-specific granularity in source data.

eligible_collateral.base_description: US-TBOND / US-TIPS (More than 5 years, up to and including 10 years)
eligible_collateral.notes: Successfully processed US Treasury collateral with 5-10 year maturity bucket. Pipeline executed 18 reasoning steps including initial parse (6 iterations), ambiguity detection (6 iterations), and 2 resolution cycles with Sonnet model achieving confidence scores of 0.885 and 0.936. Both taxonomy and logic validations passed. The collateral type was standardized, maturity range clearly defined, and haircut/valuation percentages properly calculated (4% haircut = 96% valuation). High confidence due to: (1) clean taxonomy mapping to US_TREASURY, (2) unambiguous maturity bucket definition, (3) mathematically consistent haircut-valuation relationship, and (4) successful validation on both passes. Minor confidence reduction from 1.0 due to multiple processing iterations suggesting initial ambiguities that required resolution.

eligible_collateral.base_description: US-TBOND / US-TIPS (More than 10 years, less than 30 years)
eligible_collateral.notes: Successfully parsed US Treasury collateral with 10-30 year maturity bucket at 96% valuation (4% haircut). Processing involved 6 initial parse attempts, 6 ambiguity detection passes, and 5 resolution cycles with sonnet model achieving confidence scores ranging from 0.844 to 0.936. All taxonomy and logic validations passed. The multiple resolution attempts suggest some complexity in the source data, but consensus was reached on a single maturity bucket structure. Final confidence reflects strong model agreement (avg ~0.89) and successful validation, though multiple iterations were needed for convergence.

Successfully processed US Treasury collateral with single maturity bucket. Initial parse completed across 6 iterations, followed by 6 ambiguity detection passes. Three ambiguity resolution cycles were executed with confidence scores of 0.885, 0.936, and 0.86, indicating iterative refinement of maturity bucket boundaries and haircut interpretation. All taxonomy and logic validations passed. No maturity constraints specified (null values) suggests this haircut applies universally to all US Treasury maturities. Final confidence reflects strong consensus across resolution cycles (average 0.894) with successful validation, though null maturity boundaries introduce minor uncertainty about scope applicability.

csa_terms.valuation_agent: For Paragraphs 3 and 5, the party making the demand under Paragraph 3 in respect of the applicable Valuation Date unless there has occurred and is continuing any Event of Default, Potential Event of Default or Additional Termination Event with respect to such party, in which case the other party shall be the Valuation Agent; if both parties are making a demand, see rules in Paragraph 13(d)(i)(A). For Paragraph 6(d), the Secured Party.
